Here's a JavaScript function that checks for valid prime numbers within an array and prints them to the console:

```javascript
function findPrimeNumbers(arr) {
  function isPrime(num) {
    if (num <= 1) return false;
    if (num === 2) return true;

    for (let i = 2; i <= Math.sqrt(num); i++) {
      if (num % i === 0) return false;
    }

    return true;
  }

  arr.forEach((num, index) => {
    if (isPrime(num)) {
      console.log(`Prime number found at index ${index}: ${num}`);
    }
  });
}

const numbers = [3, 13, 15, 29, 31, 51];
findPrimeNumbers(numbers);
```

When you call `findPrimeNumbers()` with an array of numbers `[3, 13, 15, 29, 31, 51]`, it will print "Prime number found at index X: Y" to the console, where X is the index and Y is the prime number found. In this example, the prime numbers found are 3, 13, 29, and 31.

Here's a simple HTML/CSS/JavaScript example that simulates a fake chatbot modal with 4 messages (2 from human, 2 from bot). Note that this example doesn't include styling for a perfect UI look, but it should give you a good starting point.

**index.html:**
```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8">
  <title>Fake Chatbot Modal</title>
  <style>
   .modal {
      position: fixed;
      display: none;
      z-index: 10;
    }
   .modal-content {
      background: #fff;
      max-width: 400px;
      padding: 20px;
      border: 1px solid #ccc;
    }
   .message {
      margin-bottom: 20px;
      border-radius: 5px;
      box-shadow: 0 0 5px #eee;
    }
  </style>
</head>
<body>
  <button id="chatbot-modal-button">Chatbot Modal</button>
  <div id="modal" class="modal">
    <div class="modal-content">
      <div class="messages">
        <ul id="message-list">
          <!-- 4 messages will be dynamically added here -->
        </ul>
      </div>
      <form id="message-form" action="">
        <input id="message-input" type="text" placeholder="Type here...">
        <button id="send-button">Send</button>
      </form>
    </div>
  </div>

  <script src="https://code.jquery.com/jquery-3.5.1.min.js"></script>
  <script>
    const modal = document.getElementById('modal');
    const messageList = $('#message-list');
    const messageInput = $('#message-input');
    const sendButton = $('#send-button');

    const chatbotMessages = ['Bot: Hello!', 'Bot: How can I help you?', 'Bot: I don\'t understand...', 'Bot: Thank you!'];
    let humanMessages = [
      'User: Hi!',
      'User: What\'s your name?',
      'User: Goodbye!'
    ];

    // Function to add messages to the list
    const addMessage = (messageText, speaker) => {
      const message = $('<li class="message">');
      message.html(`
        <div class="avatar">
          <!-- For demonstration purposes, we'll use a "user" icon -->
          <i class="far fa-user-alt"></i>
        </div>
        <div class="${speaker === 'user'?'message-human' :'message-bot'}">
          ${messageText}
        </div>
      `);
      messageList.append(message);
    };

    // Function to show the modal
    const showModal = () => {
      modal.style.display = 'block';
    };

    // Function to hide the modal
    const hideModal = () => {
      modal.style.display = 'none';
    };

    // Function to handle form submission
    const handleFormSubmit = (e) => {
      e.preventDefault();
      const messageText = $(messageInput).val();
      if (messageText.length > 0) {
        addMessage(messageText, 'user');
        const randomBotMessage = chatbotMessages[Math.floor(Math.random() * chatbotMessages.length)];
        addMessage(randomBotMessage, 'bot');
        messageInput.value = '';
      }
    };

    // Initial setup
    const messages = humanMessages.concat(chatbotMessages.slice(0, 2)); // Show 2 bot messages initially
    messages.forEach((messageText, speaker) => addMessage(messageText, speaker));
    $('#chatbot-modal-button').click(showModal);

    sendButton.click(handleFormSubmit);

    $('#modal').click((e) => {
      if (e.target === modal ||!modal.contains(e.target)) {
        hideModal();
      }
    });
  </script>
</body>
</html>
```

When you run this code, you'll see a modal with 4 messages, the first 2 from a human and the next 2 from the bot. The `randomBotMessage` variable in `chatbotMessages` array is used to select a random bot message each time a human message is sent (excluding the initial 2 bot messages). The modal will remain open until you click anywhere outside of it, and you can close it by clicking the "X" button or pressing the 'Esc' key.

In TypeScript, you can use type unions or type guards to inform the type system about potential, but limited, types in a specific context, while still ensuring that the type remains clear and consistent elsewhere in your code.

1. Type Unions:
If you're certain that the value might have multiple potential types but, in practice, it will be only one of the union members at any given time, you can use type unions like this:

```typescript
type MyUnion = Type1 | Type2 | Type3;

let myValue: MyUnion;
myValue = Type1; // This is the actual value

// TypeScript infers the type of myValue as Type1, even though the variable is declared with MyUnion
// However, it checks at runtime that myValue doesn't have a different type
const result1: myValue is Type1 = myValue as (myValue is Type1); // true
const result2: myValue is Type2 = myValue as (myValue is Type2); // false

// Type guards help to avoid potential runtime errors
function processValueAsType1(value: MyUnion): void {
  if (value === Type1) {
    // do something with Type1 value
  }
}
```

2. Type Guards:
When dealing with type unions, type guards are particularly useful, especially when working with conditional types or runtime checks. They allow you to narrow down the type of a variable based on a condition:

```typescript
function getConcreteType(value: MyUnion): Type {
  return value === Type1? Type1 : Type2;
}

let myConcreteType = getConcreteType(myValue);
// myConcreteType is Type1

// You can still use type unions when necessary, but with type guards, you inform the type system which type is the most likely or actual in this context.
```

By using type unions and type guards, you can communicate the "I know the value will only have this one type in practice" message to TypeScript, while still allowing other parts of your code to use more specific types. This helps keep your code type-safe and maintainable.

